    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">…don’t do this. I’m willing to give you all the benefit of the doubt that this was a typo, but if it wasn’t?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Then please, for the love of God, <em>do not do this.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There’s a very specific subset of the population that talks this way — or to be fair, a very specific subset of the population that talked that way <em>first</em>. And according to your viewership statistics, <a href="https://letter.ly/cable-news-viewership-statistics/" target="_self">that subset only constitutes a fifth of your viewership</a>, at most.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">“This summer about to be lit?”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Black people talk that way.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Not all black people talk that way, of course. And not only black people talk that way, of courser. And the etymology of the word “lit,” beyond its standard usage as an offshoot of “light,” <a href="https://genius.com/a/what-does-lit-mean" target="_self">reveals a history that dates back decades and crosses all manner of cultural and denotational lines</a>, of coursest. But the word’s resurgence in the past few years, especially in the context in which you used it right there? That’s black shit, stemming from the predominantly black world of hip-hop. And the invisible “is” in that sentence, which would be virtually reflexive to a native speaker of AAVE? That’s very black shit indeed.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Honestly, typo or not, I’d be much more willing to let it slide if there wasn’t an entire political movement that’s currently latched onto another loanword from AAVE. “Woke” has gone from inside baseball among the hallowed halls of Black Twitter to a reflexive conservative catchall to lambast anything that breathes the wrong way in their direction — and a good chunk of the time, that “anything” has more than a couple shades of black in it. Woke brands, woke culture, woke mobs, woke ideologies, <a href="https://www.huffpost.com/entry/tom-cotton-washington-monument_n_5ee3170ac5b67fa8b892423d" target="_self">woke obelisks</a>, for George’s sake. For all intents and purposes, <a href="https://melmagazine.com/en-us/story/woke-with-a-hard-r-how-the-right-created-a-new-dogwhistle" target="_self">woke has essentially become another slur</a>, and the wink-wink nudge-nudge nature of it has long worn thin.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><mark>At this point, I’d rather that they just went back to “nigger.” At least it’s more honest.</mark></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And hey, I get it. It’s a puff piece meant to give people some light after an incredibly dark year heading into the Memorial Day weekend. You don’t need some embittered internet lake goblin (we do not abide trolls here) with a keyboard and a lukewarm cup of tea to dump all over your parade. After fifteen months of isolation, I’m as ready for my post-COVID summer as anyone.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>(looks at self in mirror)</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Okay, maybe not.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Point being, after everything that’s happened in the past five or so years, and the not-insignificant role that the editorial decisions at CNN played in contributing to it, sprinkling some AAVE into your headlines isn’t cute. At all. It’s another step in a process that has played out throughout American history, as the broader society discovers something they like about black culture, adopts it as their own, and then whips back around and uses it as another cudgel to browbeat us for all of our supposed inferiorities. And after the Big Year in which America was finally supposed to have its grand racial reckoning that ultimately amounted to something north of diddly and south of squat, it’s <em>really</em> annoying.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
